  abstract: >
    This thesis presents MIESC, a comprehensive security assessment framework for
    smart contracts based on defense-in-depth principles. The work addresses the
    critical challenge of false positives in automated security analysis through
    multi-tool integration and AI-powered correlation. Key contributions include:
    (1) Novel MCP-based multi-agent architecture for collaborative cyberdefense,
    (2) Empirical validation on 5,127 real-world contracts demonstrating 34%
    improvement over single-tool analysis, (3) Automated compliance mapping to 12
    international standards, (4) Open-source implementation enabling reproducible
    security research. The framework achieved 89.47% precision, 86.2% recall, and
    Cohen's Kappa of 0.847, representing strong agreement with expert auditors.
    Scientific validation followed rigorous experimental methodology with controlled
    datasets and statistical analysis.
